<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-09-23T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-09-23T03:00:00-05:00" n="94" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/9–2349: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-09-23T16:00:00+08:00">September
                                    23, 1949—4 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received September 24—10:43 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>779. Radio reports during past few days give much publicity to statements
                            British Government intends recognize Communist Government as soon as set
                            up. American business men here anxious learn whether US Government
                            proposes similar action in order determine their course action.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>